When whispers fill the chamber of the mind,
While gilded quacks invent a soothing voice,
We sift the tangled clues and hope to find
And trade a careful proof for easier choice.
The market glows and boasts the perfect day,
Where reason, dimmed, concedes to painted light;
Each vendor trims his story to a sweeter say,
And timid minds accept the velvet night.
So quick we take the comfort, then forget,
Those cunning lines that wave as information;
We wake with sober eyes to rue and regret,
For truth, not rumor, heals—despite information.
